<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="557" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,363,679]" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,363,390]" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Most desbribed species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrank" authorityYear="1802" box="[578,678,364,390]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Agrotera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[578,678,364,390]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">Agrotera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share a similar forewing pattern, but their genitalia are diverse. The genus can be recognized by the third segment of the labial palpus triangularly shaped on the ventral surface, and a large notch on the junction between the 2 
<superScript attach="left" box="[615,631,435,449]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">nd</superScript>
and 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[700,714,435,449]" fontSize="6" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">rd</superScript>
segments formed by having rather short scales; the basal part of the sub-triangular forewing always yellow or yellowish white mixed with orange scales, edged by the antemedial line terminally, often with a black or dark grey spot near the base of the costal margin; the basal part of the fanshaped hindwing yellow or yellowish white; abdomen yellowish or yellowish white at base dorsally; male genitalia with a divided or undivided, distally pointed valva, a slender hook-shaped clasper usually arising from below the base of the costa (sometimes T-shaped as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Qi &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Liu &amp; Qi &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[645,815,616,642]" class="Insecta" family="Crambidae" genus="Agrotera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="557" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustispina" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[645,815,616,642]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">A. robustispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[822,911,616,642]" pageId="1" pageNumber="557">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[822,911,616,642]" pageId="1" pageNumber="557" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), and juxta bifid distally; female genitalia with ductus seminalis usually originating from posterior end of the corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
